reviews.text: This place was great! We made a last-minute dinner reservation for a date night. Our waiter was so helpful and made great suggestions. He explained the dishes very well! We ordered the duck pastry for appetizers, and I got the salmon, and my hubby got the chef's creation, which was sword fish for our main entre. We almost skipped out on dessert, and I'm so glad that we didn't! 10/10

Don‚Äôt be fooled by the simple dish names‚Äî these plates are the exact opposite. Everything on the menu is so creative! The crispy potato was incredible, by far the best potato salad I‚Äôve ever had. The pan-seared scallops was my favorite dish of the night, but the pavlova was not far behind. The blueberry elderflower sorbet was the best sorbet I‚Äôve ever had, straight up. Kevin was an awesome waiter‚Äî excellent service and very personable. I recommend sitting at the chef‚Äôs bar, it‚Äôs so much fun to watch the kitchen at work. Next time I‚Äôm in Nashville, I will be back!

Had a nice dinner at Etch last night with my wife‚Äîclose to the Country Music Hall of Fame (could
make for a good combo)

We ordered the beet salad, scallops, and the filet‚Äîand honestly, each dish had its moment.

Started with the Beet & Berry Salad, though calling it a ‚Äúbeet salad‚Äù might be generous‚Äîthere were just a couple of lonely beet slices and more greens. The goat cheese semifreddo? Tasted more like a frozen cheesecake than goat cheese‚Ä¶ which I guess might be the point? Overall, the salad leaned very sweet, between the berries and the semifreddo, and felt like it was missing a little acidity to balance things out.

The mains, though, were strong. The scallops were beautifully cooked‚Äîtender, buttery, and the kind of dish that makes you pause mid-convo. The filet was just as solid‚Äîjuicy, tender, and backed up by some great sauces: beef jus, red wine gastrique, and a tarragon shallot butter.

Service was friendly and on top of things, but the vibe felt a little... office building or corporate.

All in all, good food and solid execution, but for $214 before tip ($258 all in for one salad, two entr√©es, two wines and a cocktail), I had to go with 4 stars. Worth trying, but you‚Äôre definitely paying downtown Nashville prices. Photo Note: We shared everything and they were happy to split it on two plates. BTW: One extra scallop they up charged us $13. Server said $8, so that was a bit of a miss as well - $64 for 4 scallops? Crazy times.

Spectacular for and obviously very much chef foward eating experience. A tight and curated menu of specials tailored to give a great experience at an affordable price well beyond its weight.

Every thing we got was made by hand from someone who wants you to take pride in what you are eating. Flavorful, unique, and affordable.

Food was really beautiful. Creative, tasty, came out fast. Also enjoyed the counter stool being able to see the open kitchen at work.

Best Old Fashioned in town so far!

Friendly service and nice atmosphere. A bit dark at the regular tables.

Josh took amazing care of us last night for our first, but definitely not last visit to Etch. We stopped in early and had a smoked old fashioned at the bar.  Dickel wasn‚Äôt our favorite but to each their own.  We‚Äôll try a different bourbon in it next time. They do have an amazing high end bourbon ü•É list at good prices. We had a couple with dinner.

We started with their tried and true Octopus and Shrimp bruschetta, Spectacular!!!  We also had the duck tart.  Also amazing!!

We had a concert to get to so we were in a little bit of a hurry but Josh made sure we were well taken care of and on time.  We had the chefs creation, swordfish over succotash and the trio de setas.  Amazing depth of flavor in both and we thoroughly enjoyed them.

We received a quick bite of chocolate üç´ ice cream with their house granola that was fantastic before heading off to the concert. We look forward to coming again and sitting and enjoying a few more items. Deb definitely has an amazing restaurant she has created!!

detailedReviews.author: Lana
detailedReviews.text:
I had high hopes walking into Etch last night, but let me just say‚Äîmy lunch at mediocre chain restaurant today tasted leagues better than almost everything that hit my table at Etch. Here‚Äôs the uncensored rundown:
‚Ä¢	Food Disaster: First dish came out astonishingly over-salted. Sent it back. The replacement: still a salty mess. At that point, I gave up complaining‚Äîclearly, the kitchen doesn‚Äôt grasp moderation. Some items might have been burnt. It was a flavor letdown from start to finish.
‚Ä¢      Inferno Indoors: The temperature inside was genuinely uncomfortable. I saw staff looking wilted from the unbearable heat. It felt like Etch‚Äôs ventilation or AC was completely shot, making the place reek of garlic from the open kitchen more than ever before. A little aroma is welcome, but last night‚Äôs suffocating garlic cloud was overpowering and distracting.
‚Ä¢	Staffing Shortfall: Service felt stretched, and the back-of-house seemed just as stressed. When food quality tanks and plates keep coming out wrong, it‚Äôs a sure sign of management not caring enough.

Management: Your restaurant‚Äôs got a reputation to protect. Don‚Äôt let it slip away because of bad air, burnt food, and gallon buckets of salt.

detailedReviews.author: Josh Fuchcar
detailedReviews.text:
Deb Paquette, I don't know you personally, but you've done a great thing here.

I'll start by saying, I'm no Ducasse or Marco Pierre White; but I've worked in kitchens for years past, so I'm no stranger.

This was an all around superb way to spend an anniversary.

First impressions matter, and from the simplicity of the reservation over the phone, warm welcome at the door with complementary valet, to the personalized and handsigned gift at the table, you don't get much more pleasant than that without stepping into 'trying too hard'. Incredible balance and much appreciated. I'm used to the usual 'happy such and such event' written on the dessert plate, or the candle in the cheesecake, but this was far more delicate and intentional.

Now it must be said; and it needs to take a portion of this review... Justin, brother, you made the entire experience what it should always be.
From the kind questions you asked about us and our anniversary, to the shared joy of us both being new parents and all the joys that come with it. And of course, the test of knowledge between two fellow food and drink lovers, I was thoroughly challenged and impressed. Thank you for treating us not as mere customers, but as if we were long time friends. Whether it's policy or not, the complementary mocktail for my pregnant wife without prompting was not only delicious and unique in flavor, but wholly appreciated as she got to feel included in what she and I call the 'special drink' part of the evening.

Without boring anyone, we ordered the everything seasoned rolls, duck tart, and a shared beet/berry salad to start. Simplicity always wins, especially when you can balance flavors, accomplish intrigue, and please the eye all at the same time. The flavors were complex enough to feel novel, the textures weren't overdone, and the semifreddo utilizing goat cheese was that hint of eclectic I came to love.

Entrees were:
The classic filet mignon, with a near perfect gastrique and well prepared broccolini, and the ever clever dots of bright carrot dijon. Beautiful in visuals, classically delicious in flavor.
And the chef's special of the evening, the yellow tail over an asian fris√©e salad was simple, properly prepared, and dusted nicely for texture. It's hard to comment on how good the flavor was as the dish appeared to be already consumed before I gave it much more thought. We'll consider that a win.

I may have gone overboard with the sides but there are no regrets. A special thank you to the kitchen for your special gift to me, to those of you who worked tonight, thank you, it's small gestures that really make you stand apart not only as a restaurant but as a fully integrated staff focused on guest care.

While dessert may not have been the highlight, seeing as our bellies were full, our hearts were warm, and our palates treated exquisitely... We were yet again impressed by the simplicity of a polenta cake that satisfied that warm/cold nostalgic dessert with the texture of a cornbread, the delicate quenelle of fennel ice cream, and the decadent peach caramel sauce.

I cannot implore one enough to, at the very least, save your money... and spend it here.

The guest care, option to watch the kitchen in action, knowledgeable and personable staff? Great reason to visit. Food that doesn't aim to satisfy ostentatious attitudes, but instead focuses on preserving inventiveness and staying true to the title of eclectic without sacrificing flavor or wandering into the 'weird for weird's sake'? Quite possibly the reason you'll keep coming back.

I look forward to our next visit, and again, Deb Paquette, you've got something to be proud of.

detailedReviews.text: Hands down, the best restaurant I‚Äôve ever been to. 5 stars isn‚Äôt high enough to speak of the quality of food and service we received. I brought my girlfriend here for her birthday dinner, sitting at the chefs bar where we got to see each dish carefully curated and brought out‚Ä¶ what an amazing experience. We ordered the beet salad, octopus and shrimp on homemade foccacia and the filet minion. The bar was set so high from this one dinner that we have changed our plans for the remainder of our trip to eat at Etch because their quality of food is next to the best. I learned all about the owner (Deb‚Ä¶ whoever you are‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre my idol and I‚Äôm going to the culinary institute just because if you came from there‚Ä¶ I must go there)‚Ä¶ and am so grateful for this experience!

detailedReviews.text: Foodies. I dined here alone while on a work trip. So welcoming and comfortable, I ordered From the Sea and the Pavlova for dessert. The food was perfection. The salmon was smoky with hints of sweet cranberry and orange. The Pavlova though -I was crazy about‚Äîlight, with meringue perfection and the elderberry sorbet was just phenomenal. A must try if you are in town.

detailedReviews.author: Jay Jones
detailedReviews.text:
Finally had a chance to take military leave and return to my home state of Tennessee. I brought my family to this restaurant, only to be refused service because the staff couldn‚Äôt understand my Tennessee driver license. It has a military restriction code 30, which clearly indicates I‚Äôm on active duty.

Despite explaining this, the bartender, manager, and GM all refused to serve me. So we left and took our business to the Hampton restaurant instead.

It was an embarrassing experience for my family. Completely unacceptable. I won‚Äôt recommend this place to anyone.

For future reference, a quick Google search or even a call to local law enforcement would‚Äôve cleared it up. I guess I should be flattered they think I look under 21.

Save your money and go somewhere that is worth it.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
Unfortunately, I‚Äôm unable to respond directly to Allison‚Äôs message, but let‚Äôs call this what it is ‚Äî just another excuse to save face online.

I‚Äôm going to share the truth about how your staff treated a service member returning home with his wife and children. If your goal was to accommodate, you completely failed.

I presented my valid Tennessee driver license, which includes a military restriction code that identifies me as active duty. I should not have to offer alternative ID or defend my legitimacy. I didn‚Äôt use a fake ID, and I didn‚Äôt approach anyone aggressively. Your establishment had just opened for the day at 4:30, and you had every opportunity to handle the situation professionally.

Instead, you chose to double down with excuses. If that‚Äôs the standard you hold, then it‚Äôs clear you‚Äôre not ready to welcome all guests. Thankfully, Nashville has plenty of other options. I took my family somewhere that values both their customers and those who serve this country.

detailedReviews.author: Laurie Semke
detailedReviews.text: The food was great and lots of fun.  But, it was the SERVICE that was over-the-top wonderful.  Pre-covid, best-of-Europe, Danny- Meyer-style hospitality exceptional!!  Lisa was our server and many diners were greeting her with affection and appreciation as they entered.  The entire staff was friendly, helpful and unusually hospitable.  Here is a specific....Lisa greeted us before taking the drink order asking, "any dietary restrictions or needs?"   Then she AND the manger made a point of unobtrusively assuring us that the food we were eating would be safe and cause no problems for any of the diners.  The chefs and kitchen staff went to extraordinary lengths to present the food with anything close to a questionable ingredient isolated for those who could eat it while taking care of those who could not!  I cannot say enough about the service, which was both fun and deeply encouraging.  It was not formal/stuffy/fussy, just truly hospitable!  Well done everybody at Etch!!!

detailedReviews.author: Turmeric Tamarind
detailedReviews.text: My first visit to Nashville as a woman of color. I like nice things so when I read the reviews for this restaurant I excitedly came in for the happy hour a couple hours after landing--my FIRST Nash experience and it was TERRIBLE. I sat at the bar and the bartenders didn't even acknowledge me. A few minutes later I had to ASK to see a menu... was given the regular menu but not the Happy Hour one that everyone else at the bar had. I had to ASK for the happy hour menu which the bartender seemed annoyed by. I ordered the "cocktail of the day" which was mentioned as being an Old Fashioned.. received a pink drink in a martini looking glass so I let the bartender know I ordered the cocktail of the day which was an OF--he was visibly upset and acted as if this was my error. He begrudgingly said "I can make you a new one if you don't want that" as if he was doing me a favor. CLEARLY,  not what I ordered young guy. THEN, he made a "joke" to the "Regular" seated next to me saying "do you know her?" when she replied "no" he said "well then we can be mean to her." WOW. You don't know me and these passive aggressive jokes are NOT funny.  I've never felt so unwelcomed in an establishment. And the more time I spent in Nashville I realized there were probably some racist undertones there. Great concept, TERRIBLE etiquette & service. Train staff to do a better job at welcoming people of ALL colors and backgrounds, not just the white folk seated at the bar.

detailedReviews.author: amir nejad
detailedReviews.text:
Keren‚Äôs knowledge of the menu was outstanding; she offered thoughtful recommendations and took the time to explain the chef‚Äôs vision behind several of the dishes, making our experience feel truly personalized. Her passion for the restaurant and dedication to creating an amazing guest experience absolutely shined through.

Also, Fran lost his charger and he would‚Äôve been done. She went above and beyond and made sure that his phone was charged to make sure that we had a great night.

Not to mention, this was a career dinner with physicians and another city

She was incredible. Give her a $10 raise.

detailedReviews.author: P F
detailedReviews.text: Good food if it was 2004. I can't understand the ratings for this place. Each meal came with 4 different types of mushy sauce or cream that your food sat on. Jesus, pick one chef. The bruschetta was huge and soggy. The octopus hadn't seen a sear in its life...it looked boiled. We sat for 45 minutes before we got our first bite of food. The waiter forgot to put in our appetizer order, and abandoned our drinks at the bar for 20 minutes. He also shook his head at us and gave us sass when we asked why our drinks hadn't shown up. The decor is non existent. I just don't get it. This place isn't terrible, but it's also not a good restaurant for the price.

detailedReviews.author: Erika Brookshire
detailedReviews.text: Curry soup was amazing, and the smoked salmon bowl was delicious

detailedReviews.author: Danilo Campisi
detailedReviews.text: The experience wasn‚Äôt terrible, but it didn‚Äôt live up to expectations. The menu was quite standard‚Äînothing particularly original or memorable. The food was overly salty and lacked depth. Service wasn‚Äôt exactly poor or slow, but we felt rushed throughout the meal. If the restaurant takes reservations until 10:15 PM, we expect to be served with the same care as earlier diners‚Äînot hurried. For what it was, the prices felt unjustifiably high. Overall, not the worst, but definitely not worth a repeat visit.

detailedReviews.author: Doc Mad
detailedReviews.text: During my recent Nashville jaunt, a visit to the much-lauded Etch was a non-negotiable. Whispers of their seasonal artistry and welcoming vibe had me eager. On the hospitality front, Etch absolutely delivered. We kicked things off with their celebrated roasted cauliflower and the octopus and shrimp bruschetta. While the bruschetta concept intrigued, the octopus felt a little lost on the palate. Thankfully, the scallops entr√©e arrived like a flavor revelation, easily overshadowing any appetizer missteps.

detailedReviews.author: Florence Gross
detailedReviews.text: Cuisine contemporaine, explosion de saveurs

detailedReviews.text: Go early if you can. We shared beet salad, scallops and crispy potato salad.

detailedReviews.author: Lindsey Hinkle
detailedReviews.text: I‚Äôve never loved a dish more. The mahi was incredible..everything was‚Ä¶the drinks, the staff‚Ä¶even the manger came by to check on us. We will be back!

detailedReviews.author: Maestro Maestro
detailedReviews.text:
Short eclectic menu.  Highly recommended.
Very well worth a separate trip.  Menu changes - so check ahead.

detailedReviews.author: Matt Rose
detailedReviews.text: Stopped in for dinner and had an amazing time! Everyone from first walking in the door were great! Wish I could remember the servers name but she was  the best! Great recommendations and attention to detail. I‚Äôll be going back for that horseradish Cesar salad and the filet that was cooked to perfection!

detailedReviews.author: Justabob
detailedReviews.text: I don't like writing negative reviews - I prefer to enjoy myself - but my experience at Etch requires it. A combination of good food and good service need to work together for an enjoyable meal especially at this price level. While the food was good if overly salty, some combination of server, kitchen prep and food delivery to table was extremely inadequate. As the meal went on, the service degenerated to the point where I was probably visably stunned by the extremely long wait for our entree. Worse, no one seemed to notice and if they did notice,  didn't care. I was so looking forward to dining at Etch but went home a very unhappy camper.

detailedReviews.author: Lily Wakim
detailedReviews.text: 100% hands-down the best blue cheese olives I‚Äôve ever had with my martini in my life. Food was great, too. The duck tart? Wow. Just wow. ü§©

detailedReviews.author: Terra Wood
detailedReviews.text: The food, service and drinks were all top notch. We visited at a friend‚Äôs request and would def eat here again.

detailedReviews.author: John Mahoney
detailedReviews.text:
Not to sound like a dick‚Ä¶  But  I‚Äôve been to the best 3 Michelin star restaurants in Asia, the US and Europe.  This place is incredible.  The food‚Ä¶it‚Äôs just soooo good.  Tokyo, New York, London, Paris, Zurich, Barcelona‚Ä¶ would it be better?  No.  It would not.

For those is the know - is it three star as in there are 20 people wandering around in suits doing nothing?  No.  Does the candle on your table morph into a truffle and lobster confection?  No.

Is it delicious so much so that on business trip you eat there every night and moved a meeting so you could have lunch there before your flight!  Yes!!

negative.author: Lana
negative.text:
I had high hopes walking into Etch last night, but let me just say‚Äîmy lunch at mediocre chain restaurant today tasted leagues better than almost everything that hit my table at Etch. Here‚Äôs the uncensored rundown:
‚Ä¢	Food Disaster: First dish came out astonishingly over-salted. Sent it back. The replacement: still a salty mess. At that point, I gave up complaining‚Äîclearly, the kitchen doesn‚Äôt grasp moderation. Some items might have been burnt. It was a flavor letdown from start to finish.
‚Ä¢      Inferno Indoors: The temperature inside was genuinely uncomfortable. I saw staff looking wilted from the unbearable heat. It felt like Etch‚Äôs ventilation or AC was completely shot, making the place reek of garlic from the open kitchen more than ever before. A little aroma is welcome, but last night‚Äôs suffocating garlic cloud was overpowering and distracting.
‚Ä¢	Staffing Shortfall: Service felt stretched, and the back-of-house seemed just as stressed. When food quality tanks and plates keep coming out wrong, it‚Äôs a sure sign of management not caring enough.

Management: Your restaurant‚Äôs got a reputation to protect. Don‚Äôt let it slip away because of bad air, burnt food, and gallon buckets of salt.

negative.author: Jay Jones
negative.text:
Finally had a chance to take military leave and return to my home state of Tennessee. I brought my family to this restaurant, only to be refused service because the staff couldn‚Äôt understand my Tennessee driver license. It has a military restriction code 30, which clearly indicates I‚Äôm on active duty.

Despite explaining this, the bartender, manager, and GM all refused to serve me. So we left and took our business to the Hampton restaurant instead.

It was an embarrassing experience for my family. Completely unacceptable. I won‚Äôt recommend this place to anyone.

For future reference, a quick Google search or even a call to local law enforcement would‚Äôve cleared it up. I guess I should be flattered they think I look under 21.

Save your money and go somewhere that is worth it.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
Unfortunately, I‚Äôm unable to respond directly to Allison‚Äôs message, but let‚Äôs call this what it is ‚Äî just another excuse to save face online.

I‚Äôm going to share the truth about how your staff treated a service member returning home with his wife and children. If your goal was to accommodate, you completely failed.

I presented my valid Tennessee driver license, which includes a military restriction code that identifies me as active duty. I should not have to offer alternative ID or defend my legitimacy. I didn‚Äôt use a fake ID, and I didn‚Äôt approach anyone aggressively. Your establishment had just opened for the day at 4:30, and you had every opportunity to handle the situation professionally.

Instead, you chose to double down with excuses. If that‚Äôs the standard you hold, then it‚Äôs clear you‚Äôre not ready to welcome all guests. Thankfully, Nashville has plenty of other options. I took my family somewhere that values both their customers and those who serve this country.

negative.author: Turmeric Tamarind
negative.text: My first visit to Nashville as a woman of color. I like nice things so when I read the reviews for this restaurant I excitedly came in for the happy hour a couple hours after landing--my FIRST Nash experience and it was TERRIBLE. I sat at the bar and the bartenders didn't even acknowledge me. A few minutes later I had to ASK to see a menu... was given the regular menu but not the Happy Hour one that everyone else at the bar had. I had to ASK for the happy hour menu which the bartender seemed annoyed by. I ordered the "cocktail of the day" which was mentioned as being an Old Fashioned.. received a pink drink in a martini looking glass so I let the bartender know I ordered the cocktail of the day which was an OF--he was visibly upset and acted as if this was my error. He begrudgingly said "I can make you a new one if you don't want that" as if he was doing me a favor. CLEARLY,  not what I ordered young guy. THEN, he made a "joke" to the "Regular" seated next to me saying "do you know her?" when she replied "no" he said "well then we can be mean to her." WOW. You don't know me and these passive aggressive jokes are NOT funny.  I've never felt so unwelcomed in an establishment. And the more time I spent in Nashville I realized there were probably some racist undertones there. Great concept, TERRIBLE etiquette & service. Train staff to do a better job at welcoming people of ALL colors and backgrounds, not just the white folk seated at the bar.
